## Legal Status — READ BEFORE BUILDING ANY REVENUE FEATURES

CRITICAL: New Jersey is one of the strictest states in the country for this
exact business model. Deep legal research completed April 2026 found the
following:

### What Is High Risk Right Now

1. DIRECT PAY-PER-LEASE INVOICING TO LANDLORDS — HIGH RISK
Under N.J.S.A. 45:15, the NJ Real Estate License Act broadly prohibits
unlicensed persons/companies from engaging in brokerage activity. The statute
defines brokerage to include "assists or directs in the procuring of prospects"
for a rental — for compensation. HouseRush literally does this. A per-lease
success fee tied to procuring a prospect is high risk regardless of what it is
called. Penalties: up to $5,000 first violation, up to $10,000 each subsequent
violation, each transaction treated as a separate offense.

2. CURRENT AGENT COMMISSION SPLIT — MODERATE-HIGH RISK
N.J.S.A. 45:15-17(k) makes it a sanctionable violation to pay "any rebate,
profit, compensation or commission to anyone not possessed of a real estate
license." The agent paying Dev a split of their commission may itself violate
this provision. A 2024 NJ Real Estate Commission consent order sanctioned a
licensed agent specifically for accepting money from an unlicensed entity for
marketing/renting-related services. This arrangement needs legal restructuring.

3. PORTABLE APPLICATION FEE FROM STUDENTS — HIGH RISK / CRIMINAL EXPOSURE
N.J.S.A. 45:15-1.2 makes it a disorderly persons offense (minimum $200 fine,
up to 30 days imprisonment) for an unlicensed person to charge or accept any
fee BEFORE a lease is executed for "assistance in locating rental housing."
This includes providing lists or contact information. Charging students $25-30
for a portable application before their lease is signed falls directly into
this provision. DO NOT BUILD until legal structure is resolved.

4. "PLATFORM FEE" OR "MARKETING FEE" LABEL DOES NOT PROTECT YOU
NJ law looks at what you actually do, not what you call the fee. The 1972
Boise Cascade case established that unlicensed entities doing prospect
solicitation violate the Act even when licensed agents are involved later.
The 2014 Jeffrey Ray enforcement case fined an online rental platform $10,000,
ordered restitution, and issued a cease-and-desist — for operating a rental
referral website with matching and appointment scheduling, even though it
called itself a "database."

5. LICENSED AGENT INVOLVEMENT DOES NOT COVER THE PLATFORM
The NJ Real Estate Commission enforcement lens is not limited to the licensed
agent. It can go after "any person, firm or corporation" engaging in brokerage
activity without a license. Dev's agent friend's license does not protect
HouseRush as a company.

### What Is Safe Right Now

FEATURED LISTING BADGE ($150/month) — SAFE
Pure advertising. Landlord pays for visibility and placement. No fee tied to
whether a lease closes. This is how Zillow structures its Premier Agent
product. Build this first and generate revenue safely while legal structure
is resolved.

### How Zillow and Apartment List Do Pay-Per-Lease Legally

Both platforms use pay-per-lease pricing legally by:
- Selling advertising exposure and lead delivery only
- Contracting with property management companies who execute leases
- Defining the fee as consideration for advertising/lead delivery, not for
  negotiating the lease
- Never representing either party or touching the negotiation
- Never coordinating showings or verifying tenants for the landlord's benefit

HouseRush currently does several things that cross this line — auction format,
bid management, winner selection, messaging system, tenant verification.
These features need legal review before attaching transaction-based fees.

### Three Paths to Legal Revenue

PATH 1 — Pure Advertising Model (safest, do this now)
Restructure everything as advertising. Featured listings, impression-based
placement, lead delivery. Never charge based on lease outcomes. Legal without
a license. This is the immediate path.

PATH 2 — Get Licensed (cleanest long term)
Form a licensed NJ brokerage entity that HouseRush operates under.
Transaction-based fees become legal. Real cost and regulatory overhead but
cleanest long-term solution.

PATH 3 — Hybrid with Counsel (middle path)
Hire a NJ real estate attorney to structure the exact relationship between
HouseRush, the agent, and landlords in a way that keeps fees on the
advertising side of the legal line. Estimated cost: $300-500 for one hour.
This is what Zillow did before launching pay-per-lease.

### Action Items Before Building Any Revenue Feature

- DO NOT build direct landlord invoicing
- DO NOT build portable application fee
- DO NOT continue agent commission split without legal restructuring
- DO build featured listing badge — this is safe
- CONSULT a NJ real estate attorney before building any transaction-tied fee
- RESEARCH forming a licensed brokerage entity or partnering with one

## Claude API Integration Plan (Decided April 2026)

ANTHROPIC_API_KEY goes in Railway environment variables.
All Claude integration lives in /server/src/lib/claude.ts

Build order:

1. Fair Housing Listing Linter (FIRST — build this week/next 30 days)
   - Model: Haiku 4.5 (fast, cheap)
   - Cost: ~$0.02 per listing
   - Fires at listing submission, before admin approval queue
   - Flags potentially discriminatory language, suggests neutral rewrites,
     logs changes
   - Protects HouseRush legally as platform operator
   - This is safe to build regardless of legal status above

2. Fraud Check on New Signups
   - Model: Haiku 4.5
   - Cost: ~$0.01 per signup
   - Combines weak signals into risk narrative with reason codes
   - Extends existing .edu email verification

3. Lease Verification MVP (build the feature, hold the billing trigger)
   - Model: Sonnet 4.6 via Claude Agent SDK (not raw API)
   - Cost: ~$0.05 per lease
   - Student uploads signed lease PDF after auction closes
   - Claude extracts: parties, address, rent, dates, signatures present,
     anomaly flags
   - Returns guaranteed valid JSON via structured outputs
   - BUILD the verification feature now for trust/transparency
   - DO NOT trigger pay-per-lease invoice until legal structure is resolved
   - Use TWO-AGENT PATTERN: read-only reader agent processes untrusted PDF,
     separate actor agent triggers billing. Never let untrusted content
     directly trigger billing.

Raw API vs Agent SDK:
- Raw API = single question, single answer. Use for linter and fraud check.
- Agent SDK = autonomous reasoning loop, multi-step. Use for lease
  verification.
- Both use the same package: npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
- API key obtained from console.anthropic.com, stored in Railway env vars

## Three-Layer Storage Architecture (To Build Toward)

1. Turso core DB — structured data only. IDs, bid amounts, timestamps,
   normalized lease fields, reason codes. Never raw documents.
2. Document vault — encrypted storage for lease PDFs, student ID photos,
   enrollment proof. Separate from main DB. Time-to-live on all raw
   artifacts. Access logged.
3. Model I/O logs — minimal Claude audit trail. What was sent, what came
   back, confidence score, timestamp.

